14 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
15 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 860 of Title 17, unless there is
17 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 This act shall be known and may be cited as the “GET Over
19 Congestion (Grid Enhancing Technology Over Congestion) Act”.
20 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 861 of Title 17, unless there is
22 created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. As used in this section:
24
Req. No. 3935 Page 1

1 1. “Advanced power flow controllers” means technologies that
2 modulate circuit impedance or other electrical properties to reroute
3 power flows and relieve congestion;
4 2. “Advanced transmission technologies” (ATTs) means
5 technologies that increase the capacity, efficiency, or reliability
6 of electric transmission infrastructure, including grid-enhancing
7 technologies (GETs) such as dynamic line rating, advanced power flow
8 controllers, and topology optimization; high-performance conductors;
9 and other technologies designed to reduce transmission congestion;
10 3. “Congestion” means a condition in which a lack of
11 transmission line capacity prevents the delivery of the lowest cost
12 electricity dispatched to meet load at a specific location;
13 4. “Dynamic line rating” means a system that uses real-time or
14 forecasted weather and operating conditions, including wind speed
15 and direction, to determine the transfer capacity;
16 5. “Grid-enhancing technologies” (GETs) means advanced
17 transmission technologies that increase the usable capacity of
18 existing transmission infrastructure through hardware, software, or
19 operational tools including dynamic line rating, advanced power flow
20 controllers, topology optimization, and related technologies;
21 6. “High-performance conductor” means a conductor used in an
22 electric transmission system, including advanced steel core
23 conductors, carbon fiber conductors, composite core conductors, and
24 superconductors, and where:
Req. No. 3935 Page 2

1 a. the conductor has a direct current electrical
2 resistance that is at least ten percent (10%) lower
3 than an aluminum conductor steel-reinforced (ACSR)
4 conductor with a similar diameter and weight, or
5 b. the conductor has an energy carrying capacity at least
6 seventy-five percent (75%) greater than ACSR
7 conductors of a similar diameter and weight;
8 7. “Integrated resource plan” (IRP) means a utility’s plan as
9 further defined and established in the Corporation Commission’s
10 administrative rules found in Section 165:35-37-1 et seq. of the
11 Oklahoma Administrative Code to ensure that sufficient supply-side
12 and demand-side resources are available to meet the utility’s
13 obligation to serve and to achieve public policy objectives,
14 including those prescribed by law, rule, or Commission IRP filing, a
15 rate case, or other proceeding in which an electric utility proposes
16 additions or expansions to the transmission system;
17 8. “Large load user” means new data centers, new cryptocurrency
18 mining operations, and new facilities whose primary function is
19 artificial-intelligence computing facilities that contract with an
20 electric supplier to add seventy-five (75) megawatts or greater
21 electric load per facility or in aggregate behind a single point of
22 interconnection to an electric supplier’s load. It does not include
23 residential, commercial, agricultural, or industrial ratepayers, or
24 those entities that build generation for behind-the-meter projects;
Req. No. 3935 Page 3

1 9. “Regional Transmission Organization” (RTO) means the
2 federally recognized grid operator to which the transmission owner
3 belongs, including, but not limited to, the Southwest Power Pool
4 (SPP), or a successor entity;
5 10. “Topology optimization” means software that identifies
6 switching configurations to reroute electricity and alleviate
7 transmission constraints; and
8 11. “Transmission owner” means an investor-owned electric
9 utility subject to the ratemaking and integrated resource planning
10 authority of the Corporation Commission or other entities that own
11 and operate transmission in this state and are subject to the
12 reporting requirements of the Corporation Commission but shall not
13 include privately owned transmission or generation tie lines.
14 B. A transmission owner shall work within the stakeholder
15 process of the SPP or relevant RTO to include consideration of
16 advanced transmission technologies and GETs in the SPP or relevant
17 RTO’s integrated transmission planning process. Transmission owners
18 shall, with the SPP or relevant RTO, analyze and study:
19 1. The cost-effectiveness of advanced transmission technologies
20 as an alternative strategy to meet electric system needs;
21 2. Whether the technologies would:
22 a. increase transmission capacity,
23 b. increase transmission efficiency,
24 c. reduce transmission system congestion,
Req. No. 3935 Page 4

1 d. reduce curtailment of energy generation resources,
2 e. increase reliability,
3 f. reduce the risk of igniting wildfire,
4 g. increase resiliency, or
5 h. increase capacity to connect new energy resources; and
6 3. The technical feasibility and cost of installing one or more
7 advanced transmission technologies to address grid congestion.
8 C. A transmission owner shall analyze and study congestion hot
9 spots, consulting the SPP or relevant RTO as necessary, to cost-
10 effectively maximize the delivery of energy resources in the near
11 term, including:
12 1. Identifying the ten most congested locations on the entity’s
13 transmission system; and
14 2. Estimating the cost of congestion at each location and the
15 increased cost to ratepayers resulting from the substitution of
16 higher-priced electricity.
17 D. A transmission owner shall include in each of its integrated
18 resource plans or annual reports as required:
19 1. The results of any analysis described in subsection B of
20 this section;
21 2. The results of any analysis described in subsection C of
22 this section; and
23 3. A summary of its existing and planned ATTs and GETs that are
24 located in this state or that benefit customers in this state.
Req. No. 3935 Page 5

1 E. Transmission owners shall give reasonable consideration, but
2 not be required, to deploy ATTs and GETs projects that have been
3 identified in the RTO process as and which deployment would result
4 in ratepayer net cost savings.
5 F. Transmission owners may consult with large load users
6 outside of the RTO process to identify opportunities for voluntary
7 collaboration, cost-sharing, or customer-funded pilot deployment of
8 ATTs and GETs to reduce congestion and minimize impacts to the
9 general rate base.
10 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
